  "summary": "Leonard Walpole reacts with alarm when his lawyer, Mr. Mehren, reveals that Miss French left him an inheritance in her will. Mehren notes that the maid, Janet MacKenzie, testified that Miss French intended for Walpole to receive the money. Walpole dismisses MacKenzie as a jealous and suspicious woman who either misunderstood Miss French's intentions or falsely believes he coerced the deceased.\n\nRegarding the night of the murder, MacKenzie testified that she returned to the house at 9:45 PM to retrieve a shirt sleeve pattern and heard a man and Miss French talking in the sitting room. Walpole uses this to claim an alibi, asserting he arrived home at 9:20 PM and that his wife, Mrs. Roman, can vouch for his whereabouts. Walpole maintains that an intruder killed Miss French with a crowbar after forcing a window, but Mehren observes that the stolen items were of little value and the evidence regarding the window is unconvincing.\n\nAs the consultation progresses, Walpole becomes hesitant. He admits he required money for his wife but denies that Miss French believed he was a bachelor planning to marry her. Following the meeting, Mehren travels to a shabby house near Paddington Green to interview Mrs. Roman. He is met by a maid and eventually by Mrs. Roman, a calm, pale woman with black hair and high cheekbones, who inquires about her husband.",
